Task 3: Identifying a Client.

Objective: Find a real-world client (individual, business, non-profit, etc.) who has a problem that can be addressed with a computer science solution.

Examples of Problems:

Small Business Inventory Management: Developing a system to track and manage inventory efficiently.

Educational Resource Access for Remote Learning: Creating an online platform to provide accessible educational resources.

Finding a dog walker: Building a solution to be able to find dog walkers on-demand. 

Healthcare Appointment Scheduling System: Designing a system to streamline appointment scheduling for a clinic.

Student Resume Feedback Portal: Establishing an online portal for experts to provide feedback on student resumes.

D2L Submission: 

Individual submission of personal perspectives and expectations about collaboration 

Group agreement on collaboration 

Details of the client and brief problem statement (200 words)

Phase 2: Problem description and Solution Design (10%)
Due: Sunday, March 22, 11:59 pm

Task 1: Gathering Details from the Client

Objective: Clarify and collect all necessary details from the client about the problem.

Method: Conduct meetings, surveys, or interviews with the client to gather comprehensive information about the problem.

Task 2: Creating a Design Document

Objective: Design a computer science solution to the identified problem.

Components of the Design Document:

Introduction: Description of the problem and its significance.

Requirements Analysis: Detailed analysis of the client’s needs. (from your Phase 1)

Proposed Solution: A clear description of the proposed solution, including technical specifications, any software, and hardware requirements.

System Architecture: Diagrams and explanations of the system architecture, including data flow and user interface (can be hand-drawn or digital).

Implementation Plan: Timeline and resources required for implementing the solution.

D2L submission: A comprehensive design document summarizing the problem, client’s requirements, constraints, and any relevant data, your proposed solution, system architecture and implementation plan  (1500 words minimum, you can include images, tables and figure).

 

Phase 3: Analysis and Communication (10%)

Task 1: Analyzing the Design

Objective: Conduct a thorough analysis of the design for security, privacy, equity (accessibility), sustainability, ethical considerations, and potential impact.

D2L submission (Due: Sunday April 5, 11:59 pm): A final report containing the analysis, covering these aspects: security, privacy, equity, sustainability, ethical considerations, and societal impact. (2000 words minimum for the total document - 1000 words minimum for the new section on analysis and conclusion).

Task 2: Client Feedback

Objective: Communicate the design and its analysis to the client for feedback.

Method: Present the design and analysis to the client through a formal presentation or email the detailed report.

D2L submission (Due: Friday, April 10, 11:59 pm): Confirmation of client communication

 

